<HEAD>Apple and Microsoft Pause in Legal Battle To Announce New Product</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILLBRAE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>John Sculley</PERSON> and <PERSON>Bill Gates</PERSON>, putting
aside for the moment the legal battle between <ORGANIZATION>Apple Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, dined peacefully together this week and
announced an ``office on a disc'' for the <ORGANIZATION>Apple Macintosh</ORGANIZATION>.
   Gates, chairman of <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>, quipped that ``the legal
departments aren't friends.'' But he noted that the two companies
remain steadfast allies and share the same vision of the future of
computing.
   Sculley, <ORGANIZATION>Apple</ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, said his appearance at the <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>
presentation on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> ``shows that we want to be partners
together in innovation'' despite <ORGANIZATION>Apple</ORGANIZATION>'s ongoing copyright suit
against <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co</ORGANIZATION>.
   Apple and <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> are working together ``more now than at any
time in the past,'' <PERSON>Gates</PERSON> said. ``We have decided not to let (the
lawsuit) affect the other things we're doing and let it run its own
course.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION>Redmond</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Wash.</LOCATION>, recently won a round in the
courtroom fight when a federal judge issued a tentative ruling that
would substantially narrow <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION>, Calif.-based <ORGANIZATION>Apple</ORGANIZATION>'s suit
accusing <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard</ORGANIZATION> of stealing the ``look and
feel'' of the Macintosh system.
   ``<ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> has always been very clear that we don't understand
why <ORGANIZATION>Apple</ORGANIZATION> brought the lawsuit, and that we expect to win the
lawsuit,'' <PERSON>Gates</PERSON> said. ``I think the recent developments are
consistent with (our) predictions. The case is not over but it was
a very positive milestone.''
   The ``office on a disc'' for the <ORGANIZATION>Apple Macintosh</ORGANIZATION> consists of a
compact disc containing four of <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s most popular business
programs for the Macintosh _ <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft Word</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Excel</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>PowerPoint</ORGANIZATION> and
Mail _ plus documentation for each, a thesaurus and other items.
   Both companies hope the product will help spur the evolution
from floppy diskettes to compact disks for computers.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft Office</ORGANIZATION> collection on disk will be priced at <MONEY>$949</MONEY>
and is expected to be available by the end of <DATE>September</DATE>. That is a
one-third discount from what the programs would cost if bought
separately on floppy diskettes.
   Sales of <ORGANIZATION>Apple</ORGANIZATION>'s compact disc drive, which retails for about
<MONEY>$1,200</MONEY>, have been slow so far as businesses await more software for
it.
   ``This is just an introductory technology. I don't expect it to
have a major financial impact,'' said analyst <PERSON>David Bayer</PERSON> of
<ORGANIZATION>Montgomery Securities</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>. ``It's more a demonstration
of capabilities, laying the groundwork for future uses.''
</TEXT>
