<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft, last year introduced the
firm's Windows software, seen as a direct challenge to Apple.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SOFTWARE; PROBE; BUSINESS; COMPANY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  What began as a small federal inquiry into a single deal by Microsoft Corp.
has mushroomed into a full-scale investigation of virtually all the business
practices of the Redmond, Wash., firm, the software industry's most powerful
company.;    The vastly expanded Federal Trade Commission probe of Microsoft
-- which the company acknowledged Friday in a news release -- could have
profound effects throughout the computer industry.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SOFTWARE INQUIRY BY U.S. DEEPENS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> last month announced it was the subject of a narrow <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION>
investigation. It said then that the commission was examining a <DATE>1989</DATE> news
release it issued jointly with <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>
describing plans for future versions of a computer operating system.;    On
<DATE>Friday</DATE>, though, <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> said it had been formally notified by the <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> that
the commission is tackling a much larger question: allegations by other
software companies that it "has monopolized or has attempted to monopolize the
market for operating systems, operating environments, computer software and
computer peripherals" -- in other words, its entire product line.;    <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> is
not believed to be a subject of the investigation.;    <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> maintains it
has done nothing wrong and said the personal computer industry teems with
competition.;    "Microsoft is surprised and disappointed that the inquiry has
been broadened," said <PERSON>William H. Neukom</PERSON>, vice president of law and corporate
affairs. "We will continue to cooperate with this investigation. We believe
that <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> has acted in a legal and ethical manner.";    The news of the
expansion of the <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> probe did only minimal harm to <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s soaring stock,
which has made Chairman Bill Gates a multibillionaire and one of the nation's
wealthiest men. The stock fell <MONEY>$3.75</MONEY> a share to <MONEY>$107.25</MONEY> in Over-the-Counter
trading.;    <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> has a near-monopoly on operating systems for <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>
personal computers, is a leading supplier of software for the <ORGANIZATION>Apple Macintosh</ORGANIZATION>,
and is moving aggressively in computing areas expected to boom in the next 10
years, such as powerful desk-top "work stations" and new computers that use
pens instead of keyboards.;    The <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> probe could lead to a change in
<ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s business practices. But it's also of grave concern to other
companies, because firms throughout the personal computer industry must build
some guess about <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s actions into their own business plans.;    And
the mere existence of an expanded inquiry might have a chilling effect on
<ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>, making it more timid and its rivals more bold.;    In recent years,
industry executives have complained with increasing anger -- though usually
only in private -- that <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> goes beyond being a heads-up competitor and
instead uses its dominant market position in a manner that is at least unfair
and possibly illegal.;    One industry executive questioned by the <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION>, who
spoke on the condition that neither he nor his company be identified, said the
<ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> began its probe last fall with a limited set of questions but greatly
expanded the investigation's scope after hearing one industry executive after
another bitterly complain about <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s practices.;    About 15 software
companies are believed to have been questioned, and the executive said the
commission has a much longer list it now wants to pursue in this new stage of
its inquiries.;    "The <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> is surprisingly knowledgeable," he said. "They are
interested in the full context of <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s impact on the industry.";    The
executive said that <ORGANIZATION>Wordperfect Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION>Utah</LOCATION> word-processing software
company, took a lead role in lodging complaints against Microsoft.;   
<ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> sells Word, a word-processing program that competes against
<ORGANIZATION>Wordperfect</ORGANIZATION>'s product. The executive said <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> uses its profits from its
operating system division to undercut companies like <ORGANIZATION>Wordperfect</ORGANIZATION> on the
applications side.;    Others have also complained about <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s pricing
policies or about it once persuading software companies to spend <MONEY>tens of
millions of dollars</MONEY> developing products for one operating system, only to
switch to another at the last minute.;    Many companies are rankled by what
they see as <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s arrogance.;    "Microsoft is like a 6-(foot)-4
17-year-old boy. It lacks the inhibitions of a mature adult," said <PERSON>Bob
Metcalfe</PERSON>, who founded <ORGANIZATION>3Com Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and who later had a well-publicized
falling-out with <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>. "It's a billion-dollar company that has not
developed the inhibitions befitting a company of its size. It needs to be
taught a lesson, like <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> was taught in the <DATE>'50s</DATE> and <DATE>'60s</DATE>, that when you have
a huge monopoly, you have to behave differently.";    Any <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> action against
<ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> might be years away; its probes are notoriously lengthy affairs. The
<ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> will not discuss the investigation and certainly not what action, if any,
it may take.;    Federal antitrust laws are exceedingly complex but generally
bar companies from engaging in practices that lessen competition or harm
consumers.;    The <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> has only civil powers and can go to court to force a
company to change objectionable practices. Only the <ORGANIZATION>Justice Department</ORGANIZATION>, with
which the <ORGANIZATION>FTC</ORGANIZATION> works closely, can bring criminal charges.  </TEXT>
