<LEADPARA>  Microsoft stock has soared past $100, raising Chairman Bill Gates' net worth
to more than $4 billion and making him possibly the second-richest person in
America.;    On a strong thumbs-up recommendation from a leading New York
investment firm, Microsoft stock climbed more than $5 a share Wednesday,
passing its 52-week high of $102. Shares fell $2.75 on Thursday to close at
$103, but some analysts were recommending the stock to investors as a buy as
high as $130 a share.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GATES' NET WORTH SOARS INTO BOLIVIA'S NEIGHBORHOOD  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     At most recent count, Gates owned more than 40 million shares of <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>.
Based on figures in the <DATE>Oct. 22</DATE> issue of Forbes magazine's "400 Richest" list,
Gates would trail only <ORGANIZATION>Metromedia</ORGANIZATION> magnate <PERSON>John Werner Kluge</PERSON>, whose estimated
worth was <MONEY>$5.6 billion.</MONEY>;    Put in other terms, Gates' fortune rivals the
gross national products of <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Afghanistan</LOCATION>. An average American wage
earner would have to work 100,000 to 150,000 years to equal the amount. Gates
was traveling out of the country and not available for comment, but <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>
insiders say he downplays discussions of wealth and does not follow the stock
price. Ironically, he is not <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s highest-paid employee, earning
<MONEY>$261,000</MONEY> a year compared with President <PERSON>Michael Hallman</PERSON>'s <MONEY>$1.7 million</MONEY>
salary.;    The buying frenzy took hold after <ORGANIZATION>Goldman Sachs</ORGANIZATION> investment analyst
<PERSON>Rick Sherlund</PERSON> said he believed <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> will announce next week it is
entering a new market -- the development of software for computers based on a
chip from <ORGANIZATION>Mips Computer Systems Inc.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION>. The chips (known as RISC,
or reduced instruction-set computing) are used in powerful corporate,
scientific and engineering computers and networks.  </TEXT>
