<HEAD>Floodwaters Threaten Alligator Farm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Floods, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto pursuing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POWHATAN, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter ``Skeet'' <PERSON>Rogers</PERSON> put on metal
gloves, grabbed a 3-foot-long alligator and slung it into a cotton
wagon, moving it to high ground before flood waters got it.
   ``The last time we got to fooling with them, one man got 47
stitches,'' <PERSON>Rogers</PERSON> said, explaining the gloves.
   <PERSON>Rogers</PERSON>' 4,000 alligators were hatched from eggs gathered from
wild nests and raised in double-decked ponds in four
climate-controlled cinder-block buildings. Two more buildings are
under construction at his <ORGANIZATION>Bayou Pierre Gator Farm</ORGANIZATION>, located on low
land near the bayou for which it is named.
   About 200 square miles of <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION> is flooded by water from the
<LOCATION>Red River</LOCATION> and backwaters such as <ORGANIZATION>Bayou Pierre</ORGANIZATION>. Most of the land in
a sparsely settled section of the state is for farming cotton,
wheat, soybeans.
   <PERSON>Rogers</PERSON>' crop is different, though no less threatened.
   ``It's awful. The water keeps coming up,'' said <PERSON>Alice Hart</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Rogers</PERSON>' mother. ``I've been right here for 12 years, and nothing
like this has ever happened before.
   ``They'll drown. Skeet sold off some of the big ones, but the
rest will just drown, if it keeps coming up.''
   With hides bringing <MONEY>$35</MONEY> a linear foot and demand for alligator
meat high, alligator farming is a burgeoning industry in an
economically depressed state. <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION> has 92 licensed gator
farms. Two-dozen license applications are pending. Three years ago,
there were 13 alligator farms in <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>.
   Buddy Goatcher, an alligator biologist with the state <ORGANIZATION>Department
of Wildlife</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Fisheries</ORGANIZATION>, said it is possible gators could be
drowned if trapped in deep water for a long time with no firm
resting place.
   ``The farmer can't predict how long the waters will be up,''
<PERSON>Goatcher</PERSON> said. ``And you can't predict the force of the water. It
could knock down the building and send gators spewing all over the
place.''
   ``The threat is not so much to the well-being of the gators.
They'd love it,'' he said. ``The threat is losing the farm.''
   Along with the buildings and the concrete ponds, special heaters
are necessary to keep it warm enough for a good hatching rate and
optimum growth.
   ``He doesn't want a lot of cold water coming in,'' <PERSON>Goatcher</PERSON> said.
   Rogers and two helpers, <PERSON>Roy Cheatwood</PERSON> and his son, <PERSON>Roy Jr.</PERSON>,
piled homemade sandbags around pumps, heaters and other immovable
equipment, trying to protect them from the flood.
   The alligators were packed into four cotton wagons parked on a
nearby mound.
   Each gator had to be moved by hand.
   ``We can't get behind them with horses and drive them to high
ground,'' <PERSON>Rogers</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
