<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / International Company News: Outsider appointed to senior
post at Microsoft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest computer software company, has appointed <PERSON>Mr
Robert Herbold</PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION>Procter &amp; Gamble</ORGANIZATION> executive, as executive
vice-president and chief operating officer, writes <PERSON>Louise Kehoe</PERSON> in <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION>.
<PERSON>Mr Herbold</PERSON> will report directly to <PERSON>Mr Bill Gates</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> chairman and
chief executive, as a member of <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>'s 'office of the president',
succeeding the late <PERSON>Mr Frank Gaudette</PERSON>, who died in <DATE>April</DATE>.
He joins <PERSON>Mr Steve Ballmer</PERSON>, executive vice-president of sales and support,
and <PERSON>Mr Mike Maples</PERSON>, executive vice-president of products, as a member of the
office. This group shares responsibility with <PERSON>Mr Gates</PERSON> for broad strategic
and business planning for the entire company.
<PERSON>Mr Herbold</PERSON> worked for <ORGANIZATION>P&amp;G</ORGANIZATION> for 26 years, most recently as senior
vice-president for information services and advertising.
The appointment by <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> of an outsider to such a senior position is
surprising. In the past <PERSON>Mr Gates</PERSON> has expressed scepticism about the choice
of executives from other industries such as <PERSON>Mr Lou Gerstner</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> to head
computer companies.
Yesterday, however, <PERSON>Mr Gates</PERSON> said that <PERSON>Mr Herbold</PERSON>'s business experience and
management skills 'will prove invaluable in taking <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> forward as we
face new business challenges'.
<PERSON>Mr Herbold</PERSON> will be responsible for worldwide operations at <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION>,
including finance, manufacturing, distribution, logistics, information
technology, human resources, corporate services, real estate and development
and <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft Press</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
