<HEAD>First Day of Hunt Provides Victories, Defeats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf, `The first ...,' with number
of alligators taken the first night.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MH1, MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEWISTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most alligator hunters were disappointed
after the first day of <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>'s month-long gator season, but by
<DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME> some lucky ones bagged animals as long as nine feet.
   <DATE>Thursday</DATE> at sunset marked the beginning of the first legal
alligator hunt in 26 years for the lucky _ or not-so-lucky _ 230
people granted permits to catch the reptiles with harpoons, nooses,
crossbows and almost anything but a gun.
   The first night of the 30-day hunt netted about 130 alligators
in 28 designated hunting areas across the state, according to the
<ORGANIZATION>Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission</ORGANIZATION>. Thirty-eight were
bagged in the <LOCATION>Everglades</LOCATION>, while 36 were taken in the <LOCATION>Lake
Okeechobee</LOCATION> area, a spokesman said.
   Two novice hunters, <PERSON>David</PERSON> and <PERSON>Jerry Navin</PERSON>, snaked through a <LOCATION>Dade
County</LOCATION> canal in the darkness looking for the red-reflecting eyes
that give away the swimming reptiles, but the gators refused to
cooperate.
   ``There's a few here, but they're not really doing what they're
supposed to,'' chuckled <PERSON>David Navin</PERSON>. ``They're a little tougher
than we thought.''
   His brother <PERSON>Jerry</PERSON> called their experience ``on-the-job
training.''
   To the north on <LOCATION>Lake Okeechobee</LOCATION>, one of the designated hunting
areas, some gator pursuers reported better luck.
   <PERSON>Thomas Alpern</PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION>Brooklyn</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>, the only northerner
receiving a permit, bagged a nine-footer despite worrying
beforehand that he might be unable to kill the animal even when he
captured it.
   With gator hides selling for <MONEY>$42</MONEY> a foot and meat running up to
<MONEY>$6</MONEY> a pound, <PERSON>Alpern</PERSON> and others persevered, though few expected to
bag their 15-gator limit the first night.
   Hide and meat sales from a single alligator can total <MONEY>$300</MONEY> to
<MONEY>$500</MONEY>.
   ``We're having fun,'' said <PERSON>Bud Wolfe</PERSON>, an alligator hunter from
<LOCATION>Oakland Park</LOCATION>. ``Where else but in <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> can you go after a
500-pound animal that can kill you?''
   Early success came to <PERSON>Carlos Donate</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> and his guide, <PERSON>Jay
Medore</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Clewiston</LOCATION>. They snagged a 8-foot-3-inch animal only 80
minutes after they started hunting on <LOCATION>Lake Okeechobee</LOCATION>.
   Once they got the gator reeled up to the side of the boat, they
shot it with a ``bang stick,'' a firearm-like gadget that is
allowed under the game commission rules.
   ``We blew one hell of a hole in his head,'' <PERSON>Donate</PERSON> said. ``It
was exciting.''
   He then taped the gator's mouth shut.
   ``It's scary putting that tape on his mouth, even with a hole in
his head,'' he said.
   <PERSON>Doug Mackie</PERSON> and <PERSON>Steve Prater</PERSON>, who work for the city of <ORGANIZATION>Pembroke
Pines</ORGANIZATION>' utilities department, bagged a 6-foot alligator and another
that was 8 feet or longer.
   Prater showed how he hooked one just beside the alligator's left
rear leg with a large hook on a heavy-duty saltwater fishing rod.
He said fighting the gator when it was hooked was very difficult,
and he snapped the heavy fiberglass rod.
   ``It was a deep-sea rod and it just plain snapped in two,'' he
marveled.
   Alligator hunting was outlawed in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> in <DATE>1962</DATE> because
wildlife biologists feared overhunting of the ancient reptiles
might threaten the survival of the alligator.
   A small alligator industry has built up in recent years because
alligators have increasingly become problems by turning up in urban
areas and pestering and occasionally killing humans or their pets.
   Estimates place the current number of alligators living in
<LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> at <MONEY>1 million</MONEY>, and game commission officials said they are
now far from an ``endangered'' species.
</TEXT>
