<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to install floating toilets for the
convenience of boaters on reservoirs east and west of here aren't
exactly getting flushed down the tubes by concerned officials.
   ``It may seem that this is something kind of frivolous, but when
you think about it, when you gotta go, you gotta go,'' <LOCATION>Maricopa
County</LOCATION> parks Director <PERSON>Bill Richwine</PERSON> said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   For a boater on the northeast corner of <LOCATION>Lake Pleasant</LOCATION>, ``your
only alternative is to go ashore and get behind a cactus or go over
into the water and do it,'' <PERSON>Richwine</PERSON> said.
   Richwine envisions two floating toilets anchored in the upper,
more remote regions of the lake about 25 miles northwest of <LOCATION>Phoenix</LOCATION>.
   Each would be a one-holer restroom floating on pontoons. They
would have holding tanks similar to those in the portable toilets
used at construction sites, golf tourneys and concerts.
   <PERSON>Richwine</PERSON> said he would make the county <ORGANIZATION>Board of Supervisors</ORGANIZATION>
privy to his plans in two weeks in order to apply for a <MONEY>$90,000</MONEY>
State Lake Improvement Fund grant to pay for the restrooms and a
trailer to haul them.
   Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> is considering putting six
floating potties on <LOCATION>Roosevelt Lake</LOCATION> about 60 miles northeast of
<LOCATION>Phoenix</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>David Killebrew</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Tonto National Forest</ORGANIZATION>.
   The toilets are part of an <MONEY>$18 million</MONEY> improvement plan for the
popular water-sports site, <PERSON>Killebrew</PERSON> said. Construction is to begin
in <DATE>1990</DATE>.
</TEXT>
